<br>
1) Don Quixote, &quot;the Ingenious Gentleman of La Mancha&quot;, Cervantes.<br>
<br>
Idealism as we all should carry it.<br>
<br>
2) Captain Nemo, &quot;Twenty-thousand Leagues Under the Sea, the Mysterious Island&quot;, Verne.<br>
<br>
Idealism as we all should live it.<br>
<br>
3) Mustafa Mond, &quot;Brave New World&quot;, Huxley.<br>
<br>
Frighteningly pragmatic.<br>
<br>
4) Raskolnikov, &quot;Crime and Punishment&quot;, Dostoevsky.<br>
<br>
All the way up to the point where the author turns his back on the character and has him crawling on his knees back to his 'god'.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
These are some of the characters from fiction I can think of off the top of my head which have left an impression in my mind.  I am a contradictory person.  I love faith, hate god.  I am an idealist trying to be pragmatic.  Many opposites appeal to me at various times, my favorites may reflect this.<br>
<br>
So many great characters, so many great stories, each (if we are fortunate), teaching us a little bit about ourselves.  Who could list them all?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
As far as characters who I might have a chance of seeing in new works (closer to the question asked, I think...)<br>
<br>
1) Camber of Culdi, various novels , Katherine Kurtz<br>
<br>
2) Raistlin, yeah, I need to say it...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Really quite difficult to list.  I generally follow authors rather than characters, so it would depend upon who is writing them.  Move along, nothing to see here...<br>
<br>
poIosefis Iceheart<br>
<br>
Not dead yet.<br>
